---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import OpportunityCard from '@/components/OpportunityCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="PLP Competitor Analysis — June 2026">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">PLP Competitor Analysis</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Product Listing Page &mdash; Analysed 9 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Six competitor product listing pages were reviewed against Myprotein's protein category
      (<a href="https://www.myprotein.com/c/nutrition/protein/" target="_blank">myprotein.com/c/nutrition/protein/</a>):
      Huel (uk.huel.com/collections/bestsellers), The Protein Works (theproteinworks.com/products/shakes),
      Optimum Nutrition (optimumnutrition.com/en-gb/collections/all-products),
      Healf (healf.com/collections/performance), Bulk (bulk.com/uk/protein/whey-protein),
      and Naked Nutrition (nakednutrition.com/collections/protein-powder).
      Fourteen opportunities were identified across all six brands. The strongest cross-competitor
      signal — appearing in three of six brands — is a product finder quiz surfaced on or near the
      listing page. The most distinctive single pattern is Healf's AI advisor embedded directly
      within the product grid. Myprotein already leads on full star ratings with review counts,
      Quick Buy, collaboration product badges, and filtering depth.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Huel ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Huel</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">uk.huel.com &mdash; Bestsellers collection</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Nutritional callouts on product cards"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="huel-nutritional-callouts-on-cards"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Every Huel product card displays protein grams and kcal directly below the product name,
        using small iconographic labels — a protein icon alongside "40g protein" and a kcal badge
        alongside "400 kcal per meal". These are core card layout elements, not hover states or
        tooltip content. The Daily Greens card adapts the same pattern to its own key stat:
        "91 vitamins, minerals &amp; nutrients".
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        On a protein category page, protein content per serving is the primary purchase criterion
        for most shoppers. Surfacing it at browse level removes the need to click into a PDP just
        to answer that single question — reducing bounce and qualifying intent earlier in the funnel.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's protein PLP cards show name, rating, price, and discount — but not protein per
        serving. Adding a single nutritional callout ("25g protein per serving") to each card would
        let users compare products at browse speed. This is especially high value when comparing
        Impact Whey vs Clear Whey vs Vegan Blend, where the name alone doesn't communicate the
        nutritional difference.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Per-serving cost alongside headline price"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="huel-per-serving-unit-pricing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Huel prices every card in the format "From £30.50 / £1.79 per meal" — the consumable unit
        cost sits immediately after the headline price, adapted to the right unit per product type
        (per meal, per bottle, per serving).
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A total pack price requires mental arithmetic to compare value across different sizes and
        formats. Per-serving cost maps to daily habits ("less than a coffee") and makes cross-product
        comparison effortless — which drives confidence at the point of decision.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein shows £/kg on cards, which serves bulk comparison but is opaque for new shoppers.
        Showing "£X per serving" as a secondary price line — alongside the existing format — would
        serve both audiences: experienced buyers who think in £/kg, and new users who think in
        cost per use.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Benefit-led product subtitle on every card"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="discovery,content"
      opportunityId="huel-benefit-subtitle-on-cards"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Every Huel card carries a one-line benefit or format descriptor in a muted secondary style
        beneath the product name — "Complete high-protein powder meal", "High-protein meal shakes",
        "Supergreens powder". These are plain-language descriptors, not marketing taglines.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Product names alone assume prior knowledge. A one-line descriptor helps browse-mode users
        understand what a product is and does without clicking into the PDP — reducing pogo-sticking
        and time-to-decision.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's protein PLP shows product names only. Adding a short benefit subtitle
        ("Fast-absorbing post-workout whey", "Light, refreshing alternative to shakes") to each card
        would help the significant segment of shoppers who don't yet understand the difference between
        Impact Whey, Clear Whey, and Vegan Protein from name alone — critical given 53 products on
        this category.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Bundle surfaced as a product card within the listing grid"
      competitor="Huel"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="huel-bundle-in-plp-grid"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Huel's "Bestseller Bundle — All our favourite products, 15 items" appears as a standard
        product card within the bestsellers grid, with sub-items listed directly on the card
        ("Meals, drinks &amp; bars", "Free T-shirt, shaker and pot"). It is browsable alongside
        individual products, not siloed to a separate bundles page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        New-to-brand shoppers who are unsure what to try are the ideal bundle buyer — but they
        won't find a bundle if it only lives in a separate section they have to actively navigate to.
        Intercepting them in the main listing grid captures the right user at the right moment.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein bundles and stacks are not currently surfaced within the protein PLP itself.
        Inserting a "Protein Starter Bundle" or "Most popular stack" card into the listing — positioned
        after the first few individual products — would expose bundle options to browse-mode shoppers
        who would otherwise never reach the bundles section, with a meaningful AOV uplift potential.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── The Protein Works ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">The Protein Works</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">theproteinworks.com &mdash; Products / Shakes</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Product tier hierarchy labelled on cards"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="tpw-tier-hierarchy-on-cards"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW labels every card with its tier: PLATINUM, GOLD, or BLACK — displayed as a prominent
        badge alongside the product name. Users understand the range hierarchy at a glance without
        needing to navigate a separate comparison page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Brands with multiple tiers of the same product type risk confusing shoppers who can't tell
        why one product costs more than another. Labelling the tier on the card removes that friction
        and creates a natural upsell path — a user who picks up a GOLD product is already aware a
        PLATINUM tier exists.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein sells Impact Whey, Impact Whey Advanced, and THE Whey as a de facto tier stack,
        but the PLP does not label these as tiers. A shopper browsing the protein category has no
        signal that THE Whey is the premium option without reading every product description.
        A lightweight tier label (e.g. "Core / Advanced / Premium") applied at card level would
        make the range architecture legible at browse speed.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Goal-based and timing-based filtering"
      competitor="The Protein Works"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="discovery,personalisation"
      opportunityId="tpw-goal-based-filtering"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        TPW's filter sidebar includes "Body Goal" (Weight Loss, Lean Muscle, Muscle Mass) and
        "When to Take" (Morning, Post-Workout, Bedtime) alongside the expected ingredient and
        diet filters. Users can filter the listing to products suited to their specific
        goal and timing.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Most shoppers browse protein by goal or routine, not by protein source or ingredient.
        Offering goal and timing filters meets users at their actual mental model — "I want
        something for after training" — rather than asking them to translate that into
        ingredient knowledge first.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's protein filters cover Protein type, Flavour, Diet, and price. Adding a
        "Goal" dimension (Build Muscle, Weight Loss, Recovery, Meal Replacement) and optionally
        a "When to take" filter would meaningfully reduce time-to-decision for goal-oriented
        shoppers, who likely represent the majority of protein buyers.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Optimum Nutrition ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Optimum Nutrition</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">optimumnutrition.com &mdash; Collections / All Products</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Expert tool integrated at category level"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Desktop"
      categories="discovery,personalisation,content"
      opportunityId="on-expert-tool-at-category"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Optimum Nutrition surfaces both a Protein Calculator tool and an "Ask Coach Optimum"
        branded expert resource linked from the category level. The calculator helps users determine
        how much protein they need based on their stats; the coach resource provides personalised
        guidance within the product context.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who know how much protein they need are better positioned to choose the right product
        and size. An expert tool in the category context addresses purchase uncertainty before it
        causes a bounce — and positions the brand as a knowledgeable partner, not just a retailer.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein has a "Fuel Coach" entry in the main nav but does not surface a nutritional
        calculator or personalised advice entry point within the protein category itself. A
        "How much protein do you need?" calculator embedded in the category page — or a "Get a
        personalised recommendation" CTA prominently placed — would serve undecided shoppers and
        drive both conversion and appropriate size selection.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Bundle savings displayed within the listing"
      competitor="Optimum Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion"
      opportunityId="on-bundle-savings-on-plp"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        A featured bundle with "Save £24.50" is displayed directly within ON's product listing,
        not relegated to a separate bundles section. The saving is the lead message on the bundle
        card, making the value proposition immediately legible.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Bundle visibility in the listing intercepts the shoppers who are most likely to buy them —
        those still in browse mode and open to suggestion — rather than requiring deliberate
        navigation to a bundles page they may never visit.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        See also the same pattern from Huel above — this appears across two competitors and is a
        consistent signal worth prioritising.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Healf ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Healf</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">healf.com &mdash; Collections / Performance</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="AI advisor embedded within the product grid"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="discovery,personalisation"
      opportunityId="healf-ai-advisor-in-grid"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        "Ask Helix" — Healf's AI advisor — appears as an inline element within the product grid
        itself, not on a separate page or as a widget behind a click. It presents pre-populated
        contextual questions mid-scroll through the listing: "Which supplements help boost workout
        performance?", "How do I choose between powders, gels, and capsules?", "What ingredients
        support muscle growth and recovery?", "Which options are suitable for a plant-based diet?".
        Users can tap a question and get an immediate AI response without leaving the listing.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Decision paralysis is highest mid-browse, when a shopper has seen multiple products but
        hasn't committed. An AI advisor at that exact point — contextualised to the category, with
        pre-suggested questions that mirror real shopper uncertainty — addresses the uncertainty
        in the moment, rather than asking the user to navigate away to find help.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's protein category has 53 products and no in-listing decision support. An embedded
        AI advisor or contextual Q&amp;A panel — with pre-populated questions specific to protein
        ("What's the difference between whey and isolate?", "Which protein is best for weight loss?")
        — would address the most common reasons shoppers abandon the category without buying.
        Given Myprotein already has Fuel Coach, this could be a surface integration rather than
        a net-new build.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Personalised 'Picked for you' section above the main grid"
      competitor="Healf"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="personalisation,discovery"
      opportunityId="healf-picked-for-you"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Healf shows a "Picked for you" section above the main product grid, surfacing products
        curated to the individual user's profile and browsing history. Alongside this, a
        "Wearable connect" feature lets users sync devices (Whoop, Garmin, etc.) for
        body-data-driven recommendations — with the prompt appearing in the listing itself.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A personalised section at the top of a category page shortens the path to a relevant
        product for returning users and reduces the cognitive load of browsing 53+ items. It
        also signals that the brand understands the individual, increasing trust and affinity.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein has significant purchase history data across its user base. A "Based on your
        previous orders" or "Recommended for you" rail at the top of the protein category —
        visible only to logged-in users — would make the category page feel personalised for
        repeat buyers and reduce time-to-reorder for those returning to replenish.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Bulk ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Bulk</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">bulk.com &mdash; Protein / Whey Protein</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Default SKU (flavour and size) shown on the card"
      competitor="Bulk"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,discovery"
      opportunityId="bulk-default-sku-on-card"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Every Bulk product card displays the default flavour and size beneath the product name —
        "Vanilla 1kg", "Cola 400g", "Peach Iced Tea 500g". The listed price corresponds to that
        specific SKU, so users know exactly what they're getting at that price point without
        clicking in.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A card that shows a price without clarifying which size or flavour it applies to creates
        ambiguity — shoppers may click in only to find the default is not the size they wanted,
        or that the price changes on selection. Showing the default SKU on the card removes that
        uncertainty and reduces unnecessary PDP visits from curious rather than committed shoppers.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's protein cards show a price and Quick Buy without indicating which flavour
        or size the price refers to. Adding a default SKU line (e.g., "Chocolate / 1kg") beneath
        the product name would make the listing more transparent and reduce frustrated PDP
        click-throughs where the shopper finds the price was for a different size.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Per-card deal messaging with 'no code required' reassurance"
      competitor="Bulk"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,trust"
      opportunityId="bulk-per-card-deal-label"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Bulk attaches a specific deal label to each product card — "Summer Deals: Up to 75% off
        — no code required". Individual products with different deal mechanics get different labels:
        one card reads "Clearance Sale: Now or never", signalling scarcity specific to that product.
        The "no code required" phrase appears directly on the card.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Shoppers who see a discounted price often wonder if there's a code they're missing that
        would get them an even better deal. "No code required" eliminates that doubt and prevents
        the cart-abandonment behaviour of opening a new tab to search for a discount code.
        Per-card urgency labels (vs. a single site banner) are also more believable and specific.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein currently repeats the same banner message on every card — "UP TO 50% OFF | UK
        &amp; EUROPE'S NO. 1 SPORTS NUTRITION BRAND" — which becomes visual noise after the
        first few cards and doesn't provide the "no code needed" reassurance. A card-level label
        that clarifies the deal is automatic and code-free would reduce checkout abandonment driven
        by code-searching behaviour.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Naked Nutrition ───────────────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="competitor-section">
    <div class="competitor-header">
      <h2 class="competitor-name">Naked Nutrition</h2>
      <p class="competitor-url">nakednutrition.com &mdash; Collections / Protein Powder</p>
    </div>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Subscription option surfaced directly on PLP cards"
      competitor="Naked Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="conversion,personalisation"
      opportunityId="naked-subscription-on-card"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Every Naked Nutrition product card shows a one-time vs. Autoship toggle, a "Save 20%"
        subscription saving, and a delivery schedule selector (Every 4 weeks / Every 6 weeks /
        Every 8 weeks) — all visible on the card in the listing, before the user clicks into a
        PDP. The "Recommended" label appears next to the most popular delivery frequency.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Subscription converts best when surfaced early — before the user has committed to a
        one-time purchase mindset. Showing the subscription option at browse level, with the
        saving made explicit and the delivery flexibility demonstrated, makes subscribing feel
        like the natural default rather than an upsell discovered at checkout.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein's subscribe-and-save is primarily a PDP and checkout mechanic. Surfacing even
        a lightweight "Subscribe &amp; Save X%" label on protein category cards — for logged-in
        users or as a universal indicator — would expose the subscription option at the moment
        of product consideration, which is when the decision is most open.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

    <OpportunityCard
      title="Ingredient count as a transparency badge on cards"
      competitor="Naked Nutrition"
      viewport="Both"
      categories="trust,conversion"
      opportunityId="naked-ingredient-count-badge"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Naked Nutrition cards carry a prominent purity badge — "Only 1 Ingredient", "Only 2
        Ingredients", "Only 3 Ingredients" — displayed alongside the product name. This is
        their primary brand differentiator and it is communicated at browse level, on every
        relevant card.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Clean-label shoppers — a growing segment — want to know immediately that a product
        doesn't contain unnecessary additives. Surfacing ingredient count at card level means
        these shoppers don't need to read the ingredient list on every PDP; it's a browse-level
        filter they can apply visually.
      </p>
      <p slot="opportunity">
        Myprotein has Informed Choice certified products and Informed Sport certified products,
        but these certifications are not surfaced on PLP cards. A badge communicating "Informed
        Choice Certified" or a simpler quality signal at card level would serve the trust-driven
        shopper segment without requiring a PDP visit to find that information.
      </p>
    </OpportunityCard>

  </section>

  <!-- ─── Cross-competitor patterns ────────────────────────────────────── -->

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Cross-Competitor Patterns</h2>
    <p>
      Three patterns appeared across multiple competitors and represent the strongest signals
      from this review.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Product finder quiz on or near the PLP (Huel, The Protein Works, Naked Nutrition — 3/6 brands).</strong>
      Huel has "Which Huel is right for you?" persistently in the nav; The Protein Works has
      "Unsure where to start? Take our quiz" in the listing sidebar; Naked Nutrition has
      "Take The Quiz — Get up to 20% off" embedded in the listing navigation. Over half the
      competitor set surface a quiz entry point at or near the category page. Myprotein has
      no equivalent on the protein PLP despite having 53 products in the category — a range
      scale that makes a decision-support tool more valuable here than on any of the
      competitors' smaller ranges.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Nutritional callouts at card level (Huel, The Protein Works — 2/6 brands).</strong>
      Both brands surface protein per serving on product cards. Neither Myprotein nor the other
      four competitors do this on their listing pages. Given that protein content is the primary
      purchase criterion on a protein category page, this represents an easy lift with meaningful
      conversion impact — users can qualify products at browse speed rather than clicking into
      every PDP.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Bundle or starter pack surfaced within the listing grid (Huel, Optimum Nutrition — 2/6 brands).</strong>
      Both brands feature bundle products as cards within the main product grid, not siloed to
      a separate bundles page. New-to-brand shoppers — the most likely bundle buyers — find
      the bundle without having to know it exists. Myprotein's bundles are not currently
      surfaced within the protein category listing.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Areas Where Myprotein Already Leads</h2>
    <p>
      Myprotein's protein PLP is ahead of the competitor field in several meaningful areas.
      Full star ratings with numerical review counts appear on every card — four of the six
      competitors reviewed either show count only (Healf, Bulk) or no rating at all (Optimum
      Nutrition). The Quick Buy mechanic is matched by Bulk and Naked Nutrition but absent
      from Huel, The Protein Works, and Optimum Nutrition. Collaboration product badges
      (MARS®, Vimto®, Jimmy's Iced Coffee) are unique to Myprotein in this competitive set
      and serve as a discovery signal for existing fans of those brands. The Trustpilot score
      ("Over 210k reviews, 4.4 rated") in the navigation provides brand-level social proof
      that none of the six competitors match at that scale. Sub-category tabs (Whey / Isolate
      / Blends / Collagen / Vegan) give Myprotein a quick-navigation layer above the filter
      panel that most competitors lack.
    </p>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .competitor-section { margin-bottom: 56px; padding-bottom: 40px; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .competitor-header { margin-bottom: 24px; }
  .competitor-name { font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 2px; }
  .competitor-url { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.6; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .prose-section p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
